WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.660
Biden. And today I'll be talking about marginal zone lymphoma and some of the new approaches,

00:00:06.900 --> 00:00:12.840
particularly in the first line. So as you heard from the prior speakers, marginal zone lymphoma

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:20.220
is one of the, it's the second most common end of lymphoma. And it's really a hodgepodge of

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:26.980
different slow growing lymphomas. So we all face this in the clinic sometimes trying to,

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:31.580
you know, figure out if a lot of times you get a pathology report that says CD5 negative,

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:36.520
CD10 negative low-grade lymphoma with a differential, you know, marginal zone lymphoma.

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:41.520
It could be a plasmacetic, it could be a hairy cell. And this is when sometimes NGS could help

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:51.080
with MYD88 or some of the other, you know, the markers that we look at. Most common is

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:55.600
external marginal zone lymphoma. But again, you have many of them. So if you have cutaneous,

00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:56.560
you have the, the,

00:00:56.980 --> 00:01:02.020
the gastric, you have some of them that involve the salivary glands, the lungs, the livers. So

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:07.040
again, it's, it's a hodgepodge of different things. There's the nodal marginal zone lymphoma that looks

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:11.740
like a follicular lymphoma a lot of times. And then you have this clinic marginal zone lymphoma,

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:18.280
which mimics, you know, the CLL or it has leukemia. A lot of times they'll come in with

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:23.580
peripheral blood involvement, marrow involvement, clinic involvement as well. What is unique about

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:26.740
marginal zone lymphoma is it's, it's actually something that we have.

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:31.520
Some better understanding about the pathophysiology, unlike a lot of the other

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:38.380
homas. And one of the key things here is chronic antigen stimulation, whether it be with,

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:43.600
you know, infectious agents, for example, H. pylori in gastric or, or chlamydia on the,

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:49.680
in the ocular adnexal ones, hepatitis C and splenic marginal zone lymphoma or autoimmune

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:56.260
diseases like Sjogren's disease or, or lupus with some of these marginal zone lymphomas as well.

00:01:56.980 --> 00:02:05.200
The key to all these things is they lead to intracellular continuous BCR signaling which is

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:10.000
really key to marginal zone lymphoma pathogenesis. And all these at the end lead to BTK

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.060
phosphorylation and downstream activation of different pathways, including NF-kappa B, among

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:22.340
others as well. There's, of course, some unique mutations here. MYD88 is positive in about 10 to

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:26.980
15 percent of these patients, among other drivers as well.

00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:33.160
And what I'm trying to get to is, you know, a lot of these, it makes sense clinically that

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:38.680
BTK inhibition would be a very good target in marginal zone lymphoma for that reason.

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:43.300
For, for, for treatment in the first line, so observation is obviously, you know,

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:49.300
what's recommended for a lot of patients with low-bulk disease, radiation sometimes for,

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:56.620
for early stage disease, rituximab monotherapy or chemoimmune therapy is, is still recommended.

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:03.280
But we do have a key unmet need in marginal zone lymphoma, which is, we really need a

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:08.020
chemotherapy-free upfront treatment that's not just rituximab and it's for patients who have

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:13.180
bulky disease. Because at this time, still a lot, the majority of these patients are receiving

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:18.100
chemoimmune therapy. There's, of course, of course, rituximab and lenalidomide, but again,

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:23.800
it's, it's something that's not based on prospective trials. As a matter of fact,

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.620
marginal zone lymphoma, I always, you know,

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:31.780
call it the stepson of, of endo-lymphomas because most of the, the trials that we have, they've,

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:38.980
the marginal zone lymphoma patients are typically included as, as you know, in, in bigger follicular

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:44.680
lymphoma treatments. So there's actually one, it's, it's, it's, it's very interesting. We only

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:49.900
have one frontline randomized phase three trial in marginal zone lymphoma, and you're not going to be

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:54.880
very excited about it. I mean, it's chlorambucil versus rituximab, chlorambucil versus rifactimab.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:55.420
So again,

00:03:56.260 --> 00:04:02.380
there is a, you know, there's a big unmet need in generating prospective data

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:10.120
in marginal zone lymphoma, particularly chemotherapy-free options. If you ask in the

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:12.760
community, you're going to see that, you know, a lot of the patients who have bulky disease,

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:17.320
what are they getting? They're getting rituximab and namaste. What is that based on? It's mostly

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:22.960
retrospective studies and, and, and Dr. Losos had, you know, summarized a lot of these in

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:25.900
his prior presentation. As a matter of fact, we worked with,

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:30.460
you know, with Juan Aldruchio on, on, on one of these projects that we have here,

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:35.320
where we basically just looked at, you know, retrospectively at 237 patients who

00:04:35.980 --> 00:04:41.020
received rituximab and namaste, again, because of the lack of prospective data.

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:46.540
In the relapsed setting, again, there is the availability still of chemoimmunotherapy,

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:50.800
but this is where BTK inhibitors are currently approved. The only one that's currently FDA

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:55.540
approved is Xanabrutinib. In later lines of therapy, there's, of course, CAR-T-cell therapy,

00:04:55.540 --> 00:05:01.060
but again, that's based on studies, the Zuma 5 and the Transcend study that,

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:06.520
that were mainly targeting follicular lymphoma. As I mentioned, in terms of BTK inhibitors,

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:13.180
Xanabrutinib is currently the only FDA approved one. The initial approval for abrutinib,

00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:17.920
unfortunately, you know, there was a voluntary withdrawal afterwards because of the,

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:24.820
the prospective study later on, the CELINE trial, didn't meet its primary EFS. Acalabrutinib is,

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:32.680
at times, also used on an off-label basis. So, the Xanabrutinib approval came based on

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:40.840
the Magnolia study, which was a single-arm study, including 68 patients with, patients with relapsed

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:46.900
refractory marginal lymphoma who have received at least one prior line of therapy. The overall

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:52.000
response here was 68%, and you could see the different, you know, it was pretty, you know,

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.120
similar across the board between different subtypes. Of course, the CR rates and whatnot,

00:05:58.120 --> 00:06:01.480
I, you know, I don't want you to get too carried away with them because, again, the, you know,

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:07.360
once you start looking at these subgroups, the numbers, you know, are, become much smaller.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:13.000
So, there's currently an ongoing prospective phase three trial, the Mahogany study,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.200
and this will have two cohorts looking at follicular lymphoma and marginal

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:21.280
lymphoma cohorts in the relapsed setting. For the follicular lymphoma,

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:26.260
that's going to be Xanabrutinib abinituzumab versus R-squared, and in the marginal zone lymphoma

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:31.840
cohort, that's going to be Xanabrutinib rituximab versus R-squared. So, again, you know, we're going

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:36.700
to wait, but again, you know, it's great that we're now seeing, you know, interest in marginal

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:42.580
zone lymphoma with studies focusing, you know, primarily on marginal zone lymphoma rather than,

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:50.260
you know, include it as a subset of follicular lymphoma patients. We have an IIT at Moffitt

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:56.080
looking at Xanabrutinib rituximab in the first line setting. It has two arms. One is with,

00:06:56.080 --> 00:07:01.240
it's for marginal zone lymphoma, dedicated marginal zone lymphoma. The other one is for

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:06.400
follicular lymphoma. The thing about this trial is it's, you know, we wanted to generate data,

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:10.060
it's a time limited. So, as, you know, as of right now in the relapsed or factory setting,

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:15.160
typically you're doing the, you know, the BTK inhibitor till disease progression,

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:15.580
and the question is, do you really need, you know, to keep those patients indefinitely, you know,

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:16.180
to keep those patients indefinitely. So, you know, as of right now in the relapsed or factory setting,

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:16.300
typically you're doing the, you know, the BTK inhibitor till disease progression, and the question is,

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:22.180
do you really need, you know, to keep those patients indefinitely if you add rituximab to it.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:28.540
So, we have MRD data, you know, MRD samples at different time points collected, and we're

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:34.240
partnering with Natera to look at that MRD dynamics. And, you know, if we're starting to see

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:40.000
that, hey, you know, these patients are achieving MRD early on, maybe a fixed duration therapy might

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.860
make sense. So, that's gonna, you know, to be determined. And I just wanted to include like,

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:46.280
you know, just like one patient here,

00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:50.980
as a case study, this is a nodal marginal zone lymphoma, and you could see, you know,

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:56.080
clearly see here the lymph nodes, and this was the PET scan at three months, and you could see

00:07:56.080 --> 00:08:01.480
that pretty much all of them had disappeared. At this time, the overall response that we're seeing,

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:06.580
again, it's a trial in progress, but so far, the overall response has been about 100%,

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:11.980
and, you know, all the patients have responded. But again, I think the key question is,

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:15.880
how much relapses are we gonna see when we stop the Xanabrutinib,

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:22.660
and, you know, that's to be determined. And thank you. I went a bit over time. Thank you.
